The major skin diseases and sexually transmitted diseases are discussed in details (epidemiology, etiology and pathogenesis, clinical features and clinical course, diagnosis, treatment, rehabilitation and prevention). The attention paid on different skin diseases and sexually transmitted diseases vary - diseases of higher prevalence are discussed in more details (i.e. infectious skin diseases, allergodermatoses, papulosquamous disorders, reactive erythemas, autoimmune bullous diseases, sebaceous gland disorders, hair disorders, connective tissue diseases, vasculitis, skin tumours and sexually transmitted infections), but relatively less prevalent diseases (genetic skin disorders, tropical skin disorders) are also taught.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The purpose of the subject is to provide the medical students with the essentials in the diagnosis and treatment of skin diseases and sexually transmitted diseases that comprises both theoretical knowledge and skills needed to solve practical situations.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After passing the course, the students should be able to:  1) understand the principles of the nature and diagnosis of the skin diseases and sexually trasmitted diseases, as well as the basic methods of investigation used in dermatology and venereology with an ability to interpret the results,  2) understand the essentials of epidemiology, pathology, pathophysiology and immunology of the skin diseases and sexually transmitted diseases,  3) autonomously investigate the patient with skin and sexually transmitted diseases and suggest the preliminary diagnosis of major diseases including infectious skin diseases, allergodermatoses, papulosquamous disorders, reactive erythemas, autoimmune bullous diseases, sebaceous gland disorders, hair disorders, connective tissue diseases, genetic skin disorders, vasculitis, skin tumours, tropical skin disorders and sexually transmitted infections. 4) suggest further methods of investigations necessary to confirm the diagnosis in certain situations and interpret the respective results,  5) suggest and substantiate complex treatment options, including systemic and topical treatments, dermatosurgery, cryotherapy, lasertherapy and phototherapy in various skin diseases and sexually transmitted diseases. 6) understand the principles of continuity of the care of patients with skin diseases and sexually transmitted diseases, rehabilitation and prevention of above mentioned diseases.
